module.exports=[54923,a=>{"use strict";var b=a.i(7997),c=a.i(95936);a.s(["default",0,function({href:a="/"}){return(0,b.jsxs)(c.default,{className:"page-back",href:a,children:[(0,b.jsx)("svg",{width:"16",height:"16",viewBox:"0 0 16 16",fill:"none",children:(0,b.jsx)("path",{d:"M10 3L5 8L10 13",stroke:"currentColor",strokeWidth:"1.5",strokeLinecap:"round"})}),"Back"]})}])},82193,a=>{"use strict";a.s(["articles",0,[{slug:"article1",date:"March 2026",readTime:"12 min read",category:"Distributed Systems",title:"On Building Resilient Distributed Systems",excerpt:"Exploring patterns for fault tolerance and graceful degradation in modern distributed architectures.",content:[{type:"p",text:"Distributed systems fail. That's not a flaw — it's a fundamental property of any system composed of independent components communicating over a network. The question isn't whether your system will experience partial failure, but whether it degrades gracefully when it does."},{type:"quote",text:'"The network is reliable" is the first of the eight fallacies of distributed computing. Every architecture decision you make should be stress-tested against its negation.'},{type:"h2",text:"Designing for Failure Modes"},{type:"p",text:"Resilience starts before a single line of code is written. The most important exercise in distributed system design is enumerating failure modes — not to prevent them, but to understand how your system behaves when they occur."},{type:"p",text:"For every component in your architecture, ask: what happens when this is unavailable? What happens when it's slow? What happens when it returns incorrect results? The answers shape your circuit breakers, your retry logic, your fallback paths."},{type:"h2",text:"The Role of Idempotency"},{type:"p",text:"Retries are essential in distributed systems. Networks fail, services restart, timeouts happen. But retrying non-idempotent operations creates data consistency problems that are significantly harder to fix than the original failure."},{type:"p",text:"Design operations to be safe to repeat. Use idempotency keys for mutations. Build consumers that handle duplicate messages gracefully. This isn't defensive programming — it's foundational to building systems that can self-heal."},{type:"h2",text:"Observability as Infrastructure"},{type:"p",text:"You cannot reason about system behavior you cannot observe. Distributed tracing, structured logging, and fine-grained metrics aren't optional in complex systems — they're as important as the system itself."},{type:"p",text:"At Nest, we treat observability as a first-class concern from the first deployment. It's significantly harder to retrofit than to build in from the start."}]},{slug:"article2",date:"February 2026",readTime:"8 min read",category:"Systems Architecture",title:"The Case for Vertical Integration",excerpt:"Why controlling the full stack — from hardware to user interface — creates better products.",content:[{type:"p",text:"The conventional wisdom in technology product development favors horizontal specialization: use the best-in-class tool for each layer, integrate at well-defined interfaces, and swap components as better options emerge."},{type:"p",text:"We've come to believe this is often the wrong model — particularly for companies building at the intersection of hardware and software, or anyone where performance and user experience are existential concerns."},{type:"h2",text:"What Vertical Integration Actually Means"},{type:"p",text:"Vertical integration doesn't mean building everything from scratch. It means owning the interfaces between layers, so you can optimize across them. Apple doesn't just make the chip and the OS — they design the chip for the OS. That cross-layer optimization is where the real performance gains live."},{type:"h2",text:"The Interface Tax"},{type:"p",text:"Every abstraction layer has a cost. This is well understood in performance-critical systems. What's less discussed is the product design cost: when you don't own an interface, you can't change its behavior. You're constrained to what the interface exposes."},{type:"p",text:"This matters enormously in product development. The most interesting features often require cooperation across layers that were designed independently. Vertical integration makes this possible."},{type:"h2",text:"When to Apply It"},{type:"p",text:"Vertical integration has real costs — higher engineering investment, more surface area to maintain. It's the right choice when the experience you're building genuinely requires cross-layer optimization, and when you have the engineering capacity to maintain what you build."}]},{slug:"article3",date:"January 2026",readTime:"10 min read",category:"Developer Tools",title:"Rethinking Developer Experience",excerpt:"How we approach tooling design to reduce cognitive load and increase engineering velocity.",content:[{type:"p",text:"Developer experience has become a product category. But most tools that claim to improve DX are solving the wrong problem — they're reducing keystrokes when they should be reducing cognitive load."},{type:"p",text:"These are not the same thing. A tool that auto-completes boilerplate still requires you to hold the boilerplate's structure in your head. A tool that eliminates the need to think about the boilerplate at all is genuinely different."},{type:"h2",text:"Cognitive Load as the Real Metric"},{type:"p",text:"The limiting factor in software development isn't typing speed or even syntax memorization. It's the number of things a developer needs to hold in working memory simultaneously to make forward progress."},{type:"p",text:'This reframing changes how you design developer tools. Instead of asking "how do we make this faster?" ask "how do we make this require less mental state?"'},{type:"h2",text:"Progressive Disclosure in Tooling"},{type:"p",text:"The best developer tools apply the principle of progressive disclosure: show only what's necessary for the current task, but make everything else accessible when needed. The zero-config default gets you started; the escape hatches let you go deep."},{type:"p",text:"This is hard to build. It requires a sophisticated model of the user's mental state at each step, and deep investment in the defaults. But it's the difference between tools people tolerate and tools people love."},{type:"h2",text:"What We've Learned Building Canvas"},{type:"p",text:"In building Canvas, we've run into every version of this problem. The primitives that feel natural to systems engineers look alien to software developers. The abstractions that simplify common cases obscure uncommon ones. There's no clean answer — only continuous iteration driven by watching real users work."}]}],"workItems",0,[{slug:"meridian",num:"01",name:"Meridian",description:"A distributed systems platform for real-time data processing at scale. Built to handle millions of events per second with sub-millisecond latency.",tags:["Infrastructure","Rust","Go","Kubernetes"],status:"production",statusLabel:"Production",category:"Infrastructure / Data Systems",problem:"Existing streaming infrastructure required teams to manage complex clusters, tune countless parameters, and accept unpredictable tail latencies. As data volumes grew, operational overhead grew proportionally. We set out to build a platform that made high-throughput, low-latency data processing accessible — without the operational burden.",approachTitle:"Architecture",approach:["Meridian is built in Rust for its core processing pipeline, delivering deterministic performance and memory safety without a garbage collector. The control plane is implemented in Go for its excellent concurrency primitives and operational tooling ecosystem.","The system is deployed on Kubernetes and uses a custom scheduling layer to co-locate related processing units, reducing inter-node communication and improving cache locality."],outcomeTitle:"Outcomes",outcome:"In production, Meridian processes over 50 million events per second with p99 latency under 2ms. The system has maintained 99.99% uptime over 18 months of operation."},{slug:"canvas",num:"02",name:"Canvas",description:"Visual programming environment for complex system design. Enables teams to model, simulate, and deploy distributed architectures.",tags:["Developer Tools","TypeScript","WebGL","WASM"],status:"beta",statusLabel:"Beta",category:"Developer Tools / Visual Programming",problem:"Distributed system design lives in whiteboards, documentation, and tribal knowledge. There's no single tool that lets you move from architecture diagram to runnable simulation to deployment configuration.",approachTitle:"What We Built",approach:["Canvas uses WebGL for its rendering layer, enabling smooth manipulation of diagrams with thousands of nodes. The simulation engine runs in WebAssembly, giving near-native performance for complex system modeling directly in the browser.","Teams can define services, data flows, failure modes, and scaling policies visually — then export to Terraform, Kubernetes manifests, or Pulumi configs."],outcomeTitle:"Current State",outcome:"Canvas is in beta with several design partners. We're currently iterating on the simulation engine and refining the export pipeline based on feedback from production engineering teams."},{slug:"forge",num:"03",name:"Forge",description:"Unified firmware development kit bridging embedded systems and cloud infrastructure. From microcontrollers to edge computing.",tags:["Hardware Interface","C++","Embedded","IoT"],status:"development",statusLabel:"Development",category:"Hardware Interface / IoT",problem:"The gap between embedded development and cloud infrastructure is wide and expensive. Teams write custom glue code for every hardware platform, re-implementing the same patterns with subtle differences that cause hard-to-debug issues at scale.",approachTitle:"The Approach",approach:["Forge provides a hardware abstraction layer written in C++ that handles communication protocols, OTA update delivery, telemetry collection, and device management. Above the HAL, a lightweight runtime manages local state and cloud synchronization.","The kit supports ARM Cortex-M, RISC-V, and ESP32 platforms out of the box, with a clean extension interface for custom hardware."],outcomeTitle:"Current Status",outcome:"Forge is in active development. The core HAL and runtime are feature-complete. We're currently working on the cloud management console and hardening the OTA update system."}]])},43250,a=>{"use strict";var b=a.i(7997),c=a.i(95936),d=a.i(54923),e=a.i(82193);a.s(["default",0,function(){return(0,b.jsxs)("div",{className:"page-wrap",children:[(0,b.jsx)(d.default,{href:"/#research"}),(0,b.jsx)("p",{className:"section-tag",style:{marginBottom:16},children:"Research & Learning"}),(0,b.jsx)("h1",{style:{fontSize:"clamp(32px,4vw,56px)",fontWeight:300,letterSpacing:"-.025em",color:"var(--white)",marginBottom:64},children:"All Articles"}),(0,b.jsx)("div",{className:"research-list",children:e.articles.map(a=>(0,b.jsxs)(c.default,{className:"research-item",href:`/research/${a.slug}`,children:[(0,b.jsxs)("div",{children:[(0,b.jsxs)("div",{className:"research-meta",children:[(0,b.jsx)("span",{children:a.date}),(0,b.jsx)("span",{children:"·"}),(0,b.jsx)("span",{children:a.readTime}),(0,b.jsx)("span",{children:"·"}),(0,b.jsx)("span",{children:a.category})]}),(0,b.jsx)("h3",{children:a.title}),(0,b.jsx)("p",{children:a.excerpt})]}),(0,b.jsx)("span",{className:"research-arrow",children:"↗"})]},a.slug))})]})}])},40260,a=>{a.n(a.i(43250))}];

